properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Great amounts of wet, heavy snow and strong winds is expected through Tuesday morning. The rain will change to snow late this morning over the Lower St Lawrence and in the Gaspé peninsula. Total snowfall amounts are expected to approach 10 to 15 centimetres, except for locales near the Chaleur Bay that will receive around 5 centimetres. Quickly accumulating snow and reduced visibilities are expected to create difficult road conditions. The combination of this wet, heavy snow and these strong winds has the potential to cause broken tree limbs. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system over the BC north and central coasts will move southward today. By this afternoon the system will reach West Vancouver Island and upwards of 100 to 200 mm of rain could fall over that region through Tuesday morning. During that time, rainfall amounts of 50 to 75 mm could occur over most of Metro Vancouver, the Fraser Valley, Howe Sound, as well as East Vancouver Island between Nanoose Bay and Fanny Bay. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong winter storm will move from the Maritimes into Davis Strait on Monday night, bringing snow and strong winds to much of southern and eastern Baffin Island. This system will produce wind gusts of 80 to 90 km/h through many communities Monday night into Tuesday. These strong winds may combine with snow to produce periods of near-blizzard conditions. Snowfall amounts will remain low for most communities, however moderate to heavy snow is possible along portions of the eastern coast on Tuesday. This snow may end up bringing higher snowfall accumulations to Clyde River and Qikiqtarjuaq. ECCC meteorologists will continue to monitor the evolution of this system and refine the snowfall forecast as the low pressure centre approaches. The winds and snow will diminish on Tuesday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. 10 to 15 cm of snow Monday afternoon through Monday night. A low pressure system moving across the northern Prairies will bring heavy snowfall to northern Manitoba later today. Periods of light snow will begin early today across the region, then intensify late in the day. Heavy snow will move through the region overnight, easing early Tuesday morning. 10 to 15 cm of snow will fall with this system. For areas near the Saskatchewan border, snowfall amounts may be slightly less, especially near (and south of) Reindeer Lake. In these areas, the snow may become wetter and "less fluffy" or even change over to freezing rain for parts of the night. The risk for patchy freezing rain will spread southeastwards through the Thompson region overnight. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow.
